How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of the time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist bloc, as trips to the West were very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and travel of Czech tourists was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually, even in socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise, individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but one had to queue up with a sleeping bag and spend the night, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way the Czechs travel has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, that the presently favourite destination, Croatia, could not be traveled freely until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa-free travel to neighbouring Western European states was imposed, prompting a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, were not tired of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in the parks in tents, since our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was taking food (preserves, sausages, etc.) with them to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was rising and with it also the average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in the demand for travel agencies began, starting in 1997, regularly, to prepare travel using the connections of charter flights, which caused travel prices to fall incredibly compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the late 1990s, Czechs were traveling visa-free to almost every developed country except the U.S., which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened as early as 2000, when the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, thanks to a huge demand, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists depart every year to distant and hot countries. This winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this epoch, symbolizing our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, more than 15,000 Czech kroner per head have been spent on trips abroad, including expenses at the site of stay.
