Italian Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with Italy's president on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, though it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present the president with the outcome of his talks with political parties in his bid to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former EU commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The “framework is now well delineated,” he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, as Italy grapples with a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former EU commissioner Monti must pass a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain stricken confidence in Italy.
Underscoring pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets put the yield of Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be bailed out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employers' group Confindustria, told reporters after meeting with Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were considerably boosted by the backing of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, which the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the majority technocrat government that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in their efforts could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by warning that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
On Monday, Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women’s organizations.
He will end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was named Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite late last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would step down, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Rescue Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone’s current financial defenses.
Monti has said his government should last until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before moving the election forward.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that it should be made up only of technicians, an indication of his concerns about a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources noted that mutual distrust and disagreements between parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
