Park or mountain?
The architects agree on the opportunity of the call beyond controversies about fees
The municipal contest on the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-80s, at the height of the already extinct Metropolitan Corporation of Barcelona (CMB), this Administration printed some promotional pasquins of Collserola.
The pamphlet defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
Moreover, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with New York’s Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park was again placed, in the imagination of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital of the few that are not oriented in the north-south axis but above (mountain) -below (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a natural park results in this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with the wild boars in the role of the Yogi bear.
In these were until, in September, the city council called a megacompetition composed of 16 contests for as many doors to access Collserola.
A door refers to the idea of a park, no doubt.
Either that or someone wants to put doors to the field.
The question arises alone: Collserola, park or mountain?
The competition, both for its purely organizational aspect and for what it supposes of reflection on the city is the topic of conversation among all the Barcelona architects.
It’s almost a recurring theme to be grasped when two members of this ancient caste of elect recognize each other in an elevator.
And this fact gives rise, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between what three Barcelona architects, and university professors, have presented themselves.
Miguel Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, Daniel M<0xC3><0xB2>dol and Marta Bayona: the contest is timely.
For Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, after approaching the coastal front "it becomes necessary" to debate about "the mountain front", since the speech of Ildefons Cerd<0xC3><0xA0>, that of the green apples, has not been carried out.
"It is possible to start from the base that the most extensive park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things for its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex," says the architect for whom the title "gates of Collserola" encloses a "lexical trap": you should not think of them "as accesses to a park, but the delimitation of areas where you have to act."
M<0xC3><0xB2>dol, like Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n and Bayona with experience in the urban world, describes the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Dangers arising from the "uncertainty that is today projecting public space" after the experience lived in the 80s and that had in the area of the Forum "his swan song".
The first fear is the very delimitation of borders on where it can be built.
“To limit something is to set the next step,” that is, its overtaking.
“We have to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current [in reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)] can give rise to real disasters.”
More closely related to the question, M<0xC3><0xB2>dol thinks that, by simplifying, the Valais side of Collserola "can be understood as a park, that of Barcelona, not", for a mere topographical issue.
M<0xC3><0xB2>dol recalls that there is already a work done by the Patronat of Collserola that "should not fall into a broken sack", although he appreciates the opportunity that the city offers his guild to intervene in this project "from the first moment".
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe conduct that allows architects to enter the debate, but "doubt" about whether it is this technical profile that should lead the multidisciplinary teams ("all right", he points out) that have had to be created: "Architects should be just a tool".
Bayona insinuates that the answer to the question that gives title to this piece is complex, because in the bases of the contest a global vision of Collserola is lacking: "16 cross-sectional contests have been called -he says- in the mountain-sea sense, but there is no longitudinal reading, which sees and understands the area as a whole".
This causes, at least in your case, that you have chosen to participate in the 16 contests.
Otherwise, a project for one of the doors may collide in program and definition with that of the architect of the next door.
In his opinion, yes, the city council should ensure that the strip immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide, in its entirety, an area of equipment that would effect a smooth transition between the city and the green.
