Secretary Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come gives details of the plane crash in which the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven other people lost their lives
The Ministry of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter was directly impacted on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"Elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees 25 meters away where the unit lost its fuselage."
It also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport personnel.
In addition, he said that research done in the impact area does not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
"In a search, there are no parts or components of the spacecraft elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
“The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to carry passengers.
The terrain has a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
For the moment, the secretary said that it is a priority to have the results as soon as possible; however, the investigation can last several months, even up to a year.
Gilberto L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Meyer, general director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the Presidential Staff helicopter operated at cruising speed and that this happened on soft terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, listed six relevant elements in the research:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was conducted under the rules of visual flight, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
