MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Social Security Leads Research to Discover the Obesity Gene in Children and Youth; Supported by IPN Specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is leading research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of childhood and adolescence obesity', which will allow to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the participation of the population, whether or not they have the right, to go to the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out on minors, every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Mexico State West) and that since October 8, the activity has been carried out at the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Unit (Mexico State East).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day is celebrated on 14 November, she said the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on nutrition.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics are applied to all participants (we seek to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
"The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight there was also a dramatic rise," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for the markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in genes that are associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they are overweight or obese.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of you suffering from metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors hand it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV for most of the day and using means of transportation instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, that is, the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamals, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would prevent potholes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at UNAM’s Faculty of Chemistry, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a blend with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the pavement were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 bumps each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who said that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement is even adequate, the bumps could be reduced in quantity.
In his lecture A Technological Opinion of the Hollows, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory in charge develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt is that at high temperatures, near 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that on the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warned the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt binder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
By passing through the vehicles and generating efforts, this allows the forces to diffuse very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer opined.
On the asphalt binder, it abounded, a last layer called rolling binder is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt binder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the treadmill also requires having the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt binder.
When the soil gets wet, the water diffuses inside the folder and is difficult to leave, this causes softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a bump, he said, the first to wear is the bearing film and only after that the asphalt binder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be addressed at the first signs with adequate maintenance programs.
The also member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is complied with, to avoid that bumps form frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow to repair potholes easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
