This was the work of the cale<0xC3><0xB1>o who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a lophoscopist from the CTI of Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the FARC chief: "Alfonso Cano", through the matching of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists who work in the CTI sectional, that week it was the turn of "availability" to Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez worked in municipalities of the Choc<0xC3><0xB3>, where he often had to stay for more than five days in the jungle to reach the site where the corpses that had to be identified were.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after taking the corresponding courses, specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of the friction skin, that is, of the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano Eliazar was warned to wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for the Cauca in a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being from the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to bring Guillermo Le<0xC3><0xB3>n S<0xC3><0xA1>enz’s decadactyl card (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the body was, he did not recognize it for its physical appearance, as it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local farmer, without glasses and much thinner.
But the footprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the card.
His eye did not fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinz<0xC3><0xB3>n, that he was the top head of the FARC.
In Search of the Footprint
For a typist from the Sij<0xC3><0xAD>n de Cali, the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez at the press conference for the operation against "Cano" is very significant.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin for error, that can become key in solving crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, lophoscopists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the people captured.
When caught, many criminals present false ballots or have no papers.
We take the fingerprints and search the database.
The investigator said that, in a case of theft, he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, because in that place the thief had supported his hand to take out a safe full of jewelry and money.
“The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to make a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts,” he recalled.
Footprints can also rule out or reaffirm suspects in homicide cases.
They recently found a dead man, with bottles of liquor around him.
Through the investigation, it was determined that a family member could be a suspect in the crime and, indeed, a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, it does place him at the scene of the crime.
A CTI typist explained that in objects “the fingerprints are taken with chemical or physical reagents.”
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
“The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians,” the CTI expert said.
He clarified that not everything is as shown on the CSI TV show.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that is touched becomes a footprint.
However, if it can be used, if the respective matching is performed.
'Indignados' challenge authorities in New York
Hundreds of demonstrators crowded in front of Zuccotti Square to camp.
A large part attended the eviction order and moved to a nearby paruqe.
Members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged New York authorities on Tuesday as they tried to enter again, under the protection of a court order, Manhattan Square from where they were evicted early in the morning and as they tried to occupy another Big Apple park.
Hundreds of protesters were crowding in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access thanks to a court order that allows the "indignados" to recamp there, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction by occupying a park further north of the city, where there have been new arrests.
“Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp in the square again, we will settle somewhere else and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, as well as through peaceful sit-ins and demonstrations,” said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Occupy Wall Street movement.
Bray detailed that the response of the “outraged” to the eviction of their camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the place and allowing protesters to stay camped.
In addition, the "indignados" proceeded to occupy a new park located at the confluence of central Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which links New York and New Jersey, and owned by the parish of Trinity Church.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but then the police came and proceeded to arrest some of the protesters, although Bray could not confirm the specific figure, while he assured Efe that he saw several journalists who were also handcuffed.
The organization says that several hundred people had settled at that point, where a delegation of religious leaders has already moved to show support for the members of the movement and has tried to mediate with the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square, which is a privately owned precinct, remains closed pending the holding of a court hearing scheduled for Tuesday in which the legality of this morning's evacuation must be analyzed.
Some of the protesters displaced there carried and handed out copies of that court order at this time and even handed them over to the guards guarding the square, prompting "some small clashes," said Bray, who denounced that some officers struck the protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evicting Occupy Wall Street members or enforcing “laws that were issued after the occupation began or prohibiting protesters from re-entering the park with shops or other properties they previously used.”
Mayor Bloomberg told reporters that because of the court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and protesters, who he warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to resettle with tents and sleeping bags.
The councillor personally defended the early-morning eviction of Zuccotti Square, an operation in which about 200 arrests were carried out and which was decided because the protesters were "violating the law".
Bloomberg explained that he gave the order to evacuate the square because it was becoming "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and, in some cases, to harm other people," as "some businesses had received threats" and neighbors feared "for their quality of life."
“The eviction this morning was disgusting and shows that in the Bloomberg fund he is more interested in preserving the financial interests than those of American workers,” the movement’s spokesman added, accusing the mayor of “lacking respect for freedom of expression.”
“Occupy Wall Street” officials also said they plan to organize “big actions” for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions, to commemorate the two months of protests, which began on Sept. 17.
