Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the spiral of declines that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that turned into a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe that the country has suffered since World War II.
The first estimates by the Tokyo government put the material losses at $300 billion, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have been mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the gross domestic product data between July and September served to turn the page, definitely: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rate.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - is also the fastest pace of growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly explained by the resumption of the purchase of machinery to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, the companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decline in capital expenditures that was observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the real revulsion of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites to take advantage of crises to strengthen - or rebuild - infrastructures, to use the shortcomings to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable escalated by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The Stigma of the Yen
Tokyo has been entrusted to the domestic market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "safe haven values" chosen by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the euro zone and the murky forecasts of the US, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic flotation line is determined by the health of large technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, attributed their weak results between July and September to the yen price.
While markets continue to besiege peripheral EU countries, Yoshihiko Noda’s government does not let down its guard.
"We must be aware of the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said the secretary of state for economic policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) said most member countries showed clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points in the world economy highlighted that major powers are slowing down.
It dropped four tenths to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
The euro zone, even, was below the average, which is at the 100 level, with eight tenths falling to 99.13 points.
