Experts say euthanasia and assisted suicide should be legalised
Canadians Live Denying Death, Royal Canadian Society Report Says
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions and physicians to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not just in cancer cases.
Canadian society lives denying death.
In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they wish to die and make arrangements for that purpose.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which was attended by six experts from various fields, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Penal Code so that assisted suicide and euthanasia are allowed, when the patient raises such an option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
To begin, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks tenth, the study notes that “the medicalization of death in Canada has spawned a culture in which people are afraid to address the issue of death.”
With or without medication, 77 percent of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And while most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded in Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that do not coincide with the position of the Federal Government, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with persons who are not competent or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
“In Canada, euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal.”
“In Canada, assisted suicide is practiced, although it is clearly illegal,” explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians support euthanasia
Eighty-five percent of Canadians have already spoken out in favour of euthanasia, as they believe it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 survey by Angus Reid.
In addition, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of elderly or disabled people have less value.
As for people who have committed assisted suicide, 41% of respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
Regarding the maintenance or interruption of health care to a patient, the situation is not so clear, the authors of the report say.
In addition, among their recommendations, they suggest that the Penal Code indicates that the withdrawal of health care, if it has been legally refused, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The Committee of Experts also requests that healthcare professionals be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses care at the end of his or her life without fear of facing a complaint.
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions and physicians to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not just in cancer cases.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee calls for it to be considered as euthanasia and undergo the same procedures unless it serves to reduce physical pain.
Other experts expressed reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed their reservations regarding the findings of the report of the experts of the Royal Canadian Society.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has called the position of the experts who sign the report "extreme", among other things because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to the terminally ill.
“This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and over 18 can ask for help in committing suicide,” said Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value in society.
However, he adds that “in society, there are labels and limitations.”
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed “strong opposition” to the report’s findings, which she called a “pro-euthanasia manifesto.”
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, calls into question especially the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
