Introduction of a budgetary "golden rule" in the Constitution
The ruling Christian Democrat/Social Democratic grand coalition government in Austria on Tuesday decided to include a budgetary “golden rule” in the constitution to reduce the public deficit and thus prevent a possible degradation of Austria’s sovereign note by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reaches 74.6%, a figure well above the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency were reduced by a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay an additional 3 billion euros in interest each year,” said Michael Spindelegger, the Christian Democratic vice-chancellor for foreign affairs.
Austria thus responds to a request from the Brussels Summit to the member countries of the euro area of last October 26: in it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, before the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in a law with equivalent value.
The scheme adopted by the Austrian government is close to the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
Before 2017, the structural government deficit should decrease each year by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) and, from 2017, the structural government deficit of the federal state should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while the regional states, as well as the communes, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is that, by 2020/2021, the public debt will be reduced under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
