Still worried about the stability of the euro area, European stock exchanges plunged further into the negative zone on Tuesday, November 15.
In Paris, at 10 o’clock, the CAC 40 lost 1.4% and stood at 3,064 points.
The Dax lost 0.4% in Frankfurt and 0.1% in London.
“Taking into account the new tensions in relation to the yields on loans from the most affected euro area states, stock markets around the world continue to yield part of their recent gains.”
“Anxious investors are well aware of the risk of contagion,” Terry Pratt, an institutional broker at IG Markets, told Reuters.
The Tokyo Stock Exchange has closed with a 0.7% drop, renewing the concerns of market participants regarding Europe’s ability to contain the debt crisis.
“Japan, like the rest of the world, has its eyes fixed on Europe and the exchanges will continue to take place on a reduced margin of variation, so that investors will not have proof that the situation has stabilized,” Mitsushige Akino, fund manager at Ichiyoshi Investment Management, said in a statement.
The re-emergence of worries about the future of the euro zone affects the single currency, which continues to fall on Tuesday.
The euro remains at its lowest level for a month and a half.
By 10 a.m., the European currency was worth $1.3570, down 0.4%.
According to brokers, it has lost value after Chancellor Angela Merkel’s party, the CDU, which met Monday in Congress, adopted a motion that provides, in particular, the option of a country in difficulty leaving the euro area without leaving the European Union.
Italian and Spanish rates far exceed 6%
Credit rates in Italy and Spain remain at very worrying levels.
On Tuesday morning, the yield on Italian 10-year bonds reached 6.85%, while Spanish bonds with the same term offered 6.2%.
These tensions over the interest rates of the southern countries, but also France, continue to fuel the concerns of the auditors.
The head of the future Italian government, Mario Monti, has asked the markets for time to improve the situation in Italy, which risks suffocating with the weight of its debt.
The new Greek Prime Minister Lucas Papademos, for his part, has affirmed that the implementation of the decisions adopted at the Eurozone Summit on 27 October would be the "main task" of his Government.
Spain is in the spotlight of the markets, while the legislative elections will be held there on Sunday.
The spread difference between 10-year bonds in Germany and Spain has reached a new all-time high.
Waiting for growth figures for the euro area
From a statistical point of view, France recorded economic growth of 0.4% in the third quarter, a more favourable figure than the 0.3% forecast, driven by domestic consumption.
The Insee, however, has revised the second quarter figure downwards, with a 0.1% reduction in gross domestic product (GDP) rather than stagnation.
Moreover, the fourth quarter is what really worries economists.
Germany, for its part, recorded growth of 0.5% in the same period.
The first forecasts for the euro area as a whole are expected at 11 a.m., after the European Commission has warned of the risk of a new recession.
Energy policy:
Facts are worth more than dogmas.
If there is one issue that cannot be addressed by considering short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting should be the time to reflect on these issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will mean a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce electricity must be alleviated, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany stands alone in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is not the case either in Belgium, which is subjecting its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or in Switzerland, which is only intended to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few, are moving forward with their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality goes against such a discourse.
The choice of Berlin will mean an increase in the price of electricity, a greater dependence on energy due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
Europe’s wind champion, who gets 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would subtract realism from the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not manifest opposition in principle to this type of energy, according to the polls.
Let us remember that the energy policy of our country has lost to build an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs that specialize in international markets and can create non-localizable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of much of those SMEs and the loss of 6 billion euros a year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when its manufacturer is expected to collapse?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a Security Authority which exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it had no consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to reactor design and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented scope, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these advances and cooperation between the safety authorities, and French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is being studied by all the electric players who want to build a power plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subjected to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the newspaper Libération of 23 May) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac fixed the orientation by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has nearly two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a crowd of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his programme, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande confines himself to including trivialities, indicating that co-development will solve the “problem of migration”.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally profitable, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent paper summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and hurts jobs.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace domestic workers, particularly the low-skilled, by pushing for wage cuts.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are rather complementary than substitutes for domestic workers and mainly work in sectors with a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthesiologists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive influence on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Given the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migratory flows means a rise in real long-term wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, contributing on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of €150,000 to the public budgets on average throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go and look for the growth points that he lacked "with his teeth".
Those teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it just needs to think about a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but it is also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this since, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the twentieth century it has suffered the tragedies of World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that, in order for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be sufficient to exercise the vote as directly as possible.
We know, since Napoleon the Little, that it was something thought out.
Universal suffrage, while a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and may even become an “instrument of oppression,” as the former republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to turn into a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this respect, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return of the political sphere, but also the worrying sense of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence needs to be addressed in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer moving in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a disorderly way.
A blank signature on the absolute European monarch or a vacuum stop of the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to take effect, but a common, full-fledged, calm and continuous exercise of options and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis in Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that bows to the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, the one that suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers humiliation in the international sphere.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all of Europe that is slowly losing sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is for popular sovereignty to regain the helm of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the weight of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare their future through investments.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
After having fought for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
Let it be so.
But to think about it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and would lead us to a new stalemate.
We must take on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
An interest-driven revolution would not suffice.
This lesson remains applicable.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European people's sovereignty.
To build Europe, let us make Europeans.
Cards with "contactless" chips are generalized
The world show of chip cards starts on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global sales of cards with microprocessors (bank cards, phones with SIM cards, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to calculations by the Eurosmart cabinet.
The most powerful segment is contactless technology, which allows you to pay for public transport or purchases by simply bringing the card closer to a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its share is expected to continue to grow in 2012 (580 million units) and account for about 10% of the global chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe, which has long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the contactless payment sector.
About 26 million Visa bank cards already have this feature, which is accepted at 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards are being used.
But large areas work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCard Pass cards this year.
To put the upper gear, however, it is necessary for banks to make them available to their customers.
“There are two large French establishments that have committed to systematically disseminating bank cards equipped with the contactless system among their customers in the future,” said Gérard Nébouy, Managing Director of Visa Europe France.
Banks test mobile phone payment
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Currently, there are few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, indispensable to carry out transactions.
“They are lagging behind.”
“But I should finally experience a real boom next year.”
“We expect to sell between 80 and 120 million units in 2012 worldwide,” said Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
The bank Crédit agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhones of around 200 customers and collaborators will be equipped with a case that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société générale also said yesterday that it is preparing the marketing of an offer that allows its customers to pay contactless through their mobile.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the terrorist group Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (AQIM) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, about which it has long been suspected, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Algiers already “has certainty.”
“The way both organizations operate and the intelligence reports show that they are cooperating,” he said, without providing further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the runways.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the debris of the intervention, French and Nigerian researchers discovered several phone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist Axis
The study of the calls made points to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers particularly caught the researchers’ interest: one leads to a Nigerian who remained for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is supposedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is progress, but we must certainly wait until we have more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active,” says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such “supports” had become increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or in its operational modes, which now involve the use of suicide bombers or explosive devices increasingly complex and of the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since pressed Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long considered the group as an uninteresting enlightened community.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (which means, in Hausa, "Western education is a sin"), calls for the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes and demands strict respect for sharia, while its militants launch themselves into the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are oriented primarily to churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were especially active and attacks against police stations multiplied.
Abuya’s reaction was, as it usually happens, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested while alive, is killed in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, he claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, in particular the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations becomes its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist hub in Africa, which would range from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, is troubling for all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and Al-Chebab Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information".
The world according to Republican presidential candidates
In relation to China, Iran and aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry rival in simplicity and lack of knowledge.
Can an America weakened by the crisis manage a complex world with simple or even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might think so.
For the past few days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the other candidates have been making increasingly loud statements and shortcuts on foreign policy, traditionally a stronghold of Republicans.
The often unfounded slogans spread over China, Iran, aid to Israel.
Mitt Romney, the best-placed candidate in the race for nomination by the "Grand Old Party", has threatened to take the Chinese to the WTO and denounce them "for manipulating their currency", a key issue in an America exasperated by the migration of entire fragments of its sector to Asia.
It doesn’t matter if that means the explosion of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama’s former ambassador to China and the only candidate to have a sophisticated view of foreign policy, almost drowns in an attitude that “overwhelms” emotions.
He called for a firm but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama’s current position).
But Huntsman, who is stuck in the depths of the surveys, remains inaudible.
In the style of Reagan
Romney has also promised military intervention in Iran if sanctions fail to disrupt its nuclear program.
“If I get elected, I will stop Iran,” he boasted.
“If Obama gets re-elected, they’ll have the bomb.”
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing to meet his obligations to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second-highest-ranked candidate, shows embarrassing ignorance of such issues.
Recently, he urged to counter the Chinese military threat because Beijing “attempts to develop nuclear capability,” seemingly ignoring the fact that China already has the military atom since 1964.
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants to intervene in Iran, says he is willing to deploy the U.S. military to Mexico to fight drug cartels.
The use of torture against alleged terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
The differences are considerable with 2008 Republican nominee John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
Opponents of the current president reply that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They remember that Obama himself was an aficionado and that he had to loosen the piston in the fight against terrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of their naive dialogue with Iran, the hasty departure of the "boys" from Iraq and their misrepresentations in Libya, and label it weak.
But attacks are not easy for them.
People are judging Obama’s national security balance, which ended with bin Laden, rather positively.
From Iraq, he is wary of the military interventions that generate a sinking.
And, arguing that it takes economic reconstruction of America to resurrect his leadership, Obama gives the impression of being more just.
The Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia via the Baltic Sea bottom, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly communicates, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network together.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe each year through a first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipe is expected to be completed by the end of 2012 that will supply a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk about the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the overland passage by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening to shut it off from Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has achieved greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe’s energy, given that the project has generated a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in achieving its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large consumers of gas and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically unites us,” Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon confirmed during the pipeline’s inauguration, demonstrating the extent to which large gas sector contracts are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the Gazprom executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, measures to protect the fauna and flora had to be extended.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in the waters of Sweden, but those responsible for the project renounced it, seeing that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state-owned company to settle permanently at sea off its coast.
“In the event of a breakdown, we will interrupt the gas flow in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, as they have foreseen joints that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is guaranteed by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply guaranteed by the pressure.
At the beginning it is 200 bars and at the output of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch company Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the company, for a period of 25 years, all of its renewable gas transport capacity.
“Gazprom will pay you for the full capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually being transported,” Müller said.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been carried out in 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and in 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are confident they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom bears the risk of the expenses on its own.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a trademark notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back a taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a design notebook, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then the company’s consultant, was in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the stools.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has adapted an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century, to current taste,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Modo Modo.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed, has remained far away.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer’s profile, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cult.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its beginnings, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and has known how to impose his identity.
“We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, diaries, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among persons with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disheartening?
“No,” says <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.
“At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a lot to do."
It is worth mentioning that the unemployed with disabilities continue to face numerous obstacles to accessing employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In other words, there are numerous issues that make it particularly difficult to return to work and that "constitute the crux of the problem," says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; the mentality of the people advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité noted that the directors surveyed have “a low level of knowledge about disabilities”, with an “excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled”.
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law of 1987.
According to the latest figures available, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body in charge of collecting the contributions of companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created a great deal of pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees, compared to 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 employees.
Hazard: "A joy"
About to face the Bleus on Tuesday night (20:45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens do not hide the pleasure generated by this friendly match.
We will not dare to say that there was connivance between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting next to each other, on the stage of the Stade de France auditorium, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have really made peace.
Five months after his striker’s grudge against Turkey, the Belgian coach has nothing but praise for him.
“I was very happy for Eden, for his progress and because he is Belgian.”
“I want to move forward,” Lille’s striker replies.
As for the contrast between his presentations on his team and in the selection, "it's a set", it has been justified.
“In Lille, I am all year round, which does not apply to Belgium.
“I have to sit down.”
Summoned to play against Romania on Friday night, considering this match against France, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis to finally "shine".
Not to mention the “pleasure”.
He has been cheering on the Bleus since he was seven, as well as during the victorious campaigns of 1998 and 2000.
“I’ve always been a fan,” he says.
Without a doubt, this will especially reinforce the "particular" character of the meeting.
Especially because he will face “Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami),” he recalls.
“We just faced off recently.
"Playing against them is always a joy."
With simplicity, Leekens has made reference to “pride.”
"Proud" to play "a gala game."
"Proud" also to see, as "neighbor", that France "returns to be a very high level team", about a year after Knysna's trauma.
"Laurent Blanc has done a formidable job," he said enthusiastically.
While Belgium will not attend the next European competition, the coach would be delighted to share a plane with the Bleus to Brazil in 2014.
“Our little Belgians are growing up,” he said.
“We’re building something; the players are ambitious, they’re hungry.
"You'll be able to see him in the next games." Including the game against France.
